SALMONELLOSIS, STUDENTS - USA (MASSACHUSETTS)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Wed 21 Jun 2006
From: Pablo Nart <pablo.nart@terra.es>
Source: The Boston Globe [edited]
<http://www.boston.com/yourlife/health/diseases/articles/2006/06/21/11_students_in_franklin_sick_with_salmonella/>

11 students at a Franklin elementary school have confirmed cases of
salmonella, and state health officials are investigating whether owl
pellets used in a class project were the source of the bacterial infection.
Most of the sick students are 5th-graders at Jefferson Elementary
School, said Bela Matyas, the medical director of epidemiology for
the state Department of Public Health.
In a biology experiment, 5th-graders at the school pick out bones in
owl pellets to identify animals, such as mice or chicks, the owls
might have eaten. The experiment has been conducted by generations of
students across the country. A few students with salmonella who were
not in the 5th grade may have gotten the disease from a peer, Matyas said.
Other possible sources of the infection include water from turtles in
the classrooms and food consumed by 5th-graders at an event. Matyas
said the department has ruled out school cafeteria food as a source.
The Health Department is interviewing students to determine their
relationships and how they might have been exposed to the bacteria.
It has also taken samples from the students and will test the owl
pellets and turtles' water.
[Byline: Shawntaye Hopkins]
--
Pablo Nart
<pablo.nart@terra.es>
